## 9.3 Geometric objects


Same data, different geoms:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# Left
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-5-1.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
# Right
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_smooth()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'
```


:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-5-2.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
#> `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'
```
:::


Not every aesthetic works with every geom. You can't set the `shape` or a line geom.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# Left
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = drv)) + 
  geom_smooth()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'
```


:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-6-1.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
# Right
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy, linetype = drv)) + 
  geom_smooth()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'
```


:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-6-2.png){width=672}
:::
:::


Instead of giving a shape to a line geom, ggplot split the lines by `drv`.

For geoms that produce a single geometric object, you can use the `group` aesthetic to draw multiple objects. Note that the `group` aesthetic does not add a legend or distinguishing features to the geoms.



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(aes(linetype = drv))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'
```


:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-7-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


Placing mappings in a geom function overwrites the global mappings for that layer only. This means you can have different aesthetics in different layers.




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = class)) + 
  geom_smooth()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'
```


:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-8-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


You can use this idea to specify different data for each layer.



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_point(
    data = mpg |> filter(class == "2seater"), 
    color = "red"
  ) +
  geom_point(
    data = mpg |> filter(class == "2seater"), 
    shape = "circle open", size = 3, color = "red"
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::





::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# Left
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
# Middle
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +
  geom_density()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-2.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
# Right
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +
  geom_boxplot()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-3.png){width=672}
:::
:::




## 9.4 Facets


`facet_wrap()` splits a plot into subplots that each display one subset of the data based on a categorical variable.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(~cyl)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-11-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::



To facet with a combination of two variables, switch to `facet_grid()`.



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-12-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::



Let the x and y axes vary across plots with `scales = "free"`.



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl, scales = "free")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-13-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


Use the `.` to facet horizontally?


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-14-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::





::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value `binwidth`.
```


:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-15-1.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  facet_wrap(~drv)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value `binwidth`.
```


:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-15-2.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ)) + 
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_grid(. ~ drv)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value `binwidth`.
```


:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-15-3.png){width=672}
:::
:::




## 9.5 Statistical transformations

When new values have to be calculated for the plot.

-   Bar charts, histograms, and frequency polygons bin your data and then plot bin counts, the number of points that fall in each bin.

-   Smoothers fit a model to your data and then plot predictions from the model.

-   Boxplots compute the five-number summary of the distribution and then display that summary as a specially formatted box.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = cut)) + 
  geom_bar()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-16-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


The algorithm used to calculate new values for a graph is called a **stat**, short for statistical transformation.

You can see which stat a geom uses by looking at default arguments, and the documentation for a given stat can be found on the geom help page. See how `stat_count()` is documented on the `geom_bar()` help page.

Every geom has a default stat, and every stat has a default geom.

You might need to use the stat explicitly to:

1. override the default stat



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
diamonds |>
  count(cut) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = cut, y = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-17-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


2. Override default mapping from transformed variables to aesthetics.

For example, a bar chart of proportions instead of counts is possible like this:



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = cut, y = after_stat(prop), group = 1)) + 
  geom_bar()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-18-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::



3. You might want to draw greater attention to the statistical transformation in your code. Here is an example with `stat_summary()`, which summarizes the `y` value for each unique `x` value plotted.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(diamonds) + 
  stat_summary(
    aes(x = cut, y = depth),
    fun.min = min,
    fun.max = max,
    fun = median
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](chapter_09_notes_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-19-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::




